Exercises 
Q1. A load on 230V RMS draws 18A RMS and consumes 3,105W.
(a) Apparent power S
(b) Power factor and phase angle
(c) Reactive power Q
(d) Is the load inductive or capacitive?
(e) Verify with power triangle: S² = P² + Q²
Q2. Three loads in parallel on 400V RMS, 50Hz:
Load 1: 10kW, PF = 0.85 lagging
Load 2: 6kW, PF = 1.0
Load 3: 4kW, PF = 0.70 leading
(a) P_total, Q_total (careful with signs), S_total
(b) Overall PF and phase angle
(c) Total current
(d) What type of reactive compensation is needed and why?
Q3. Power factor correction: 230V, 50Hz, motor: P = 5kW, PF = 0.68 lagging.
(a) Initial current I₁
(b) Initial reactive power Q₁
(c) Correct to PF = 0.96. Find Q_C.
(d) Find capacitance C
(e) New current I₂ after correction
(f) Current reduction as percentage
Q4. Derive the real power formula from scratch:
v(t) = V_m sin(ωt), i(t) = I_m sin(ωt − φ)
Instantaneous power: p(t) = v(t) × i(t) = V_m I_m sin(ωt) × sin(ωt − φ)
Using the identity: sin(A)×sin(B) = ½[cos(A−B) − cos(A+B)]
(a) Expand p(t) using this identity
(b) Average the result over one complete cycle T. The cos(2ωt) term averages to zero.
(c) Show the average equals ½ V_m I_m cos(φ)
(d) Express in terms of V_rms and I_rms to get P = V_rms I_rms cos(φ)
(e) What does the oscillating cos(2ωt−φ) term represent physically?
Q5. A data centre has 2000 server power supplies. Each: 800W output, 92% efficiency, 230V supply, PF = 0.99 (with PFC).
(a) Input power per supply
(b) Input current per supply
(c) Total current for 2000 supplies
(d) Total reactive power Q for the whole data centre
(e) If PFC failed on all units and PF dropped to 0.55: find new total current
(f) The building transformer is rated 500kVA at 230V. How many supplies can it support with PF = 0.99? And with PF = 0.55?
